https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/ukraine-russia-putin-news-03-03-22/h_6aec23a5fbe5aee8ee448833bc6a22da</div></div>]]></description><guid>https://imgur.com/a/zwYsC9A</guid><dc:creator><![CDATA[mfrybeasley]]></dc:creator></item><item><title>Real Men need what?</title><link>https://imgur.com/gallery/tZDQnLu</link><description><![CDATA[<div><img alt="" src="https://i.imgur.com/S2o3mMw.jpg" style="max-width: 90%; height: auto;"></div><div><span></span></div><div>Art: 
J Flores
https://twitter.com/J_Flores_Draws
Thank you so much to @AmishBarn420RaiseIt for a link leading to the artist.

Text copied from or inspired by:
https://egalitarianchica.tumblr.com/

Normalize taking care of your man the same way you would want him to take care of you. Not like a little boy - he's not. Society (private and personal) have not prepared most men or women for looking at men this way or this kind of communication.

Normalize holding and kissing them when they’re sad and just because. Normalize doing nice things for them. Normalize genuinely listening to them when they’re upset. Normalize complimenting them and telling them you love and appreciate them.

It’s great that we idolize male celebrities (and men in general) for how well they love their women; we need to show women and girls what they’re worthy of. Men see this in society - sometimes it's oversold or soppy. But it's there.

But can we also start doing the reverse, idolizing female celebrities (and women in general) for how well they love their men? Men and boys need to be shown what they’re worthy of too.

This is not a momentary or a fad thing. I'm not talking about holidays and birthdays. It's a lifestyle change and takes love and commitment moments when you don't always feel like it - men do the same. 

Finally, sex was an easy target but I also don’t mean housewife stuff like cooking and cleaning. I mean that women should be affectionate with their male partners and provide them with emotional support and do sincere romantic gestures for them sometimes, not just Hallmark cards (nice but not the point here).

